  {
    "text": "The impediment to action advances action. What stands in the way becomes the way.",
    "source": "Meditations, Book V",
    "author_slug": "marcus-aurelius",
    "tradition_id": 1,
    "themes": "[\"resilience\",\"virtue\",\"reason\"]",
    "tier": "free",
    "quality_score": 0.97
  },
  {
    "text": "Waste no more time arguing about what a good man should be. Be one.",
    "source": "Meditations, Book X",
    "author_slug": "marcus-aurelius",
    "tradition_id": 1,
    "themes": "[\"virtue\",\"duty\",\"reason\"]",
    "tier": "free",
    "quality_score": 0.96
  },
  {
    "text": "Never let the future disturb you. You will meet it, if you have to, with the same weapons of reason which today arm you against the present.",
    "source": "Meditations, Book VII",
    "author_slug": "marcus-aurelius",
    "tradition_id": 1,
    "themes": "[\"control\",\"equanimity\",\"reason\"]",
    "tier": "free",
    "quality_score": 0.93
  },
  {
    "text": "Make the best use of what is in your power, and take the rest as it happens.",
    "source": "Enchiridion, Chapter 1",
    "author_slug": "epictetus",
    "tradition_id": 1,
    "themes": "[\"control\",\"equanimity\",\"virtue\"]",
    "tier": "free",
    "quality_score": 0.94
  },
  {
    "text": "He is a wise man who does not grieve for the things which he has not, but rejoices for those which he has.",
    "source": "Discourses, Book I",
    "author_slug": "epictetus",
    "tradition_id": 1,
    "themes": "[\"gratitude\",\"equanimity\",\"virtue\"]",
    "tier": "free",
    "quality_score": 0.91
  },
  {
    "text": "Seek not the good in external things; seek it in yourselves.",
    "source": "Discourses, Book III",
    "author_slug": "epictetus",
    "tradition_id": 1,
    "themes": "[\"virtue\",\"control\",\"reason\"]",
    "tier": "free",
    "quality_score": 0.92
  },
  {
    "text": "It is not that I am brave, but that I value other things more than I fear danger.",
    "source": "Discourses, Book II",
    "author_slug": "epictetus",
    "tradition_id": 1,
    "themes": "[\"courage\",\"virtue\",\"reason\"]",
    "tier": "free",
    "quality_score": 0.89
  },
  {
    "text": "It is not the man who has too little, but the man who craves more, that is poor.",
    "source": "Letters to Lucilius, Letter II",
    "author_slug": "seneca",
    "tradition_id": 1,
    "themes": "[\"gratitude\",\"equanimity\",\"virtue\"]",
    "tier": "free",
    "quality_score": 0.93
  },
  {
    "text": "Begin at once to live, and count each separate day as a separate life.",
    "source": "Letters to Lucilius, Letter I",
    "author_slug": "seneca",
    "tradition_id": 1,
    "themes": "[\"time\",\"impermanence\",\"virtue\"]",
    "tier": "free",
    "quality_score": 0.95
  },
  {
    "text": "We suffer more often in imagination than in reality.",
    "source": "Letters to Lucilius, Letter XIII",
    "author_slug": "seneca",
    "tradition_id": 1,
    "themes": "[\"control\",\"equanimity\",\"reason\"]",
    "tier": "free",
    "quality_score": 0.96
  },
  {
    "text": "Omnia aliena sunt, tempus tantum nostrum est. All things are alien to us; time alone is ours.",
    "source": "Letters to Lucilius, Letter I",
    "author_slug": "seneca",
    "tradition_id": 1,
    "themes": "[\"time\",\"impermanence\",\"control\"]",
    "tier": "free",
    "quality_score": 0.94
  },
  {
    "text": "Follow nature and you will never be poor; follow opinion and you will never be rich.",
    "source": "Fragments, via Diogenes Laertius VII",
    "author_slug": "zeno-of-citium",
    "tradition_id": 1,
    "themes": "[\"nature\",\"virtue\",\"reason\"]",
    "tier": "free",
    "quality_score": 0.88
  },
  {
    "text": "Happiness is a good flow of life.",
